where the critical value c adjusts for the multiplicity of k À 1 simultaneous inferences. One then infers dose levels with lower confidence bounds greater than D to be efficacious. If one infers the lowest dose i such that Dunnett’s lower confidence bounds for mj À m1 ; i j k, are greater than D to be MEDU ; then it is a conservative 100ð1 À aÞ% upper confidence bound on the true MED. That is, one has 100ð1 À aÞ% confidence that MEDU is a higher dose than the true MED. We now discuss several options for the critical value c. Without multiplicity adjustment, c would simply be the univariate t upper a quantile t1Àa;n : Applying the Bonferroni inequality to adjust for multiplicity is guaranteed to result in conservative inference. This amounts to using the quantile t1Àa=ðkÀ1Þ;n in place of c and pretending the events Ei ¼ fInference on mi À m1 is incorrectg; i ¼ 2; . . . ; k; are disjoint, which they are not because it is certainly possible for inferences on two or more mi À m1 to be wrong at the same time. The Bonferroni approximation is generally not very accurate for multiple comparisons with a control. Applying idk’s inequality to adjust for multiplicity is also guaranteed to result in conservative inference. This amounts to using the quantile tð1ÀaÞ1=ðkÀ1Þ ;n and pretending the events Ci ¼ Eic ¼ fInference on mi À m1 is correctg; i ¼ 2; . . . ; k; are independent, which they are not because the inferences share common estimates for m1 and s2 : The independence approximation is slightly better than the Bonferroni approximation, but generally still not very accurate for multiple comparisons with a control. The critical value c that adjusts for multiplicity exactly, so that the simultaneous confidence bounds ^ ^ (2) have coverage probability exactly 100ð1 À aÞ%, depends on a; the correlation matrix of mi À m1 , i ¼ 2; . . . ; k; and the error degrees of freedom n: If the correlation matrix has a 1-factor structure in the sense that it can be written in the form of 